//A way to define natural numbers in c++ in terms of the terms zero and successor:
class null{};
class zero{
null a;//has no capacity to represent anything, since null has no physical members.
//one might claim that the member "a" will still take physical storage but the point is that conceptually, it cant store anything. (you (my future self) can use inheritance so that the memory footprint is also completely zero, but i find a "a" member better for this representation.
};
template<typename T, typename predecessor>
struct successor: predecessor {
T a;//has a capacity of storing something
};
template<typename T>
using one= successor<T, zero>;
template<typename T>
using two= successor<T, one>;
//The point is a number is any bundle containing the same number of elements as that number.
//Zero has null because a number is the number of members in the class representing it.The number of members in a class is the number of members in classes similiar to it, Such that zero has one member but no physical capacity. One has 2 members but space for one, and so on. Peanos 5 axioms are much simpler since it presupposes that one can define zero, since zero is amongst the 3 properties whose definition is presupposed.
